cocus#Workshop: The Admin Role is the parent role of the person who is the parent of Thing and the Workshop. The Admin Role is the parent role of the person who is the parent of Thing and is the parent of the Event which was approved by the Administrator.
cocus#Event: The parent of Thing is Event which is a child of Workshop which is also the parent of Event.
cocus#Account: The Account was created by a user who is the child of the Administrator. The Administrator is the parent of the User and the Corresponding Author is the Administrator. The Administrator is the parent of the User and the Account was modified by the Person. The Account was registrated by the Person. The Account was created by the Corresponding Author.
cocus#User: The parent of the user is the parent of the child of the author who created the event. The event was created by the parent of the activity Event Tracks. The event has resulted in the creation of the Event Tracks which is a component of the event.
cocus#Role: The Committe Role is the parent of Thing and the child of Committe Role.
cocus#Help_Request: The Help Request is the parent of the Help Request which is the child of the Symposium. The Activity has resulted in a Document which is the parent of the Thing which is also the parent of the Symposium.
cocus#Symposium: Symposium is the parent of Thing and Symposium.
cocus#Abstract: Paper is the parent of Document and Thing.
cocus#Paper: The Corresponding Author is the parent of the Paper which was submitted by the Corresponding Author. The Paper is a child of the Invited Paper. The Author is the parent of the User who received the document.
cocus#Administrator: The Admin Role is the parent of Thing and the child of Reviewer Role. The Administrator is the administrator who is the executor of the role.
cocus#Document: The Document, which was received by the user, is used by the user who is the parent of Thing. The user is the child of the parent of Thing and takes part in an event.
cocus#Invited_Paper: Invited Paper is the parent of both Paper and Full Paper. Short Paper is the parent of both Paper and Full Paper.
cocus#Admin_Role: Admin Role is the parent of Thing and Admin Role.
cocus#Paper_Typologies: Paper Typologies is the parent of the Event Setup which is the event that was confirmed by Approval Email. The event is the child of the Conference and is the parent of the Email Template.
cocus#Event_Setup: The Research Topic is the parent of the Event Setup which is confirmed by an Approval Email. The Approval Email confirms the Event and it is the parent of the Thing.
cocus#Event_URL: The Event URL is the parent of Thing.
cocus#URL: The Event URL is the child of the Event URL which is the parent of the Thing. The Event URL is the parent of the Approval Email which is the parent of the Approval Email.
cocus#Notification_Email: Rejection Email is a child of Notification Email and Rejection Email.
cocus#Email: Email is received by the person who is the parent of the document. The document is reviewed and sent by the person who is the parent of the document. The document is also the source of the Feature Request. The Conference and the Workshop are both held by the person who is the parent of the document.
cocus#Short_Paper: The Corresponding Author is the parent of the document which was submitted by the Corresponding Author. The document is the parent of the document which was submitted by the Corresponding Author. Corresponding Author is the parent of the document which was submitted by the Corresponding Author. Corresponding Author can be removed from the document.
cocus#Author_Role: The Author Role is the parent of the Reviewer Role and the Admin Role. The Reviewer Role is the parent of the Admin Role.
cocus#Preview: Review Form is the parent of Preview and Event Setup. Thing is the parent of Event Setup.
cocus#Review_Form: Review Form is the parent of Preview and Review Form.
cocus#Committe_Role: Committe Role is the parent of Thing and Admin Role.
cocus#Group_Email: Group email is received by a person who is the parent of Thing. Document is the parent of Thing and is a child of Template.
cocus#Submission_Template: The Submission Template is the parent of the Event Setup which is approved by the Administrator. The Event Setup is defined by the Administrator.
cocus#Review_Form_Setup: Review Form is the parent of Preview and Review Form.
cocus#Misc: Misc is the parent of Help Request which is a child of Help Request.
cocus#Author: The author is the parent of the user and the Committee. The Administrator is the parent of the person who is the parent of the Thing. The Committee approves an event and the Administrator is the parent of the person who is the parent of the user.
cocus#Event_Creation: The event, which was created, is the parent of Thing and Symposium.
cocus#Approval_Email: The Approval Email confirms that the Event is the parent of Thing and Conference.
cocus#Rejection_Email: Rejection Email is sent to the person who is the parent of the email. The email is received by the person who is the parent of the Notification Email. The Administrator is the parent of the User who sends the Help Request. The Committee is the parent of the Administrator.
cocus#Submission: The person who sent the Help Request is the parent of the document which was removed by the person who sent the submission. The person is also the parent of the Thing and the person who sent the Help Request.
cocus#Feature_Request: Feature Request is the parent of Help Request which is a child of Feature Request and Assistance.
cocus#Committee: The author is the parent of the user and the user is the child of the author. The author is the parent of the user and the child of the Thing.
cocus#Event_Tracks: Event Setup is a child of Paper Typologies and Email Template. It is the parent of Event Tracks and also of Event Setup.
cocus#Request: The Help Request is the child of Misc and is the parent of the document Thing. This document is used by the person who is the parent of the person who is the role of the person who is the parent of the Help Request. The Activity has resulted in a Document which is used by the person who is the parent of the Help Request.
cocus#Activity: Event Setup is a child of Review Form and is the parent of Thing. It is the parent of the Review Form which is the parent of the Review Form. The event is sent by the person who is the parent of Thing and has resulted in an event.
cocus#Head_Role: The Head Role is the parent of the Head Role and the Thing Role. The Reviewer Role is the child of the Reviewer Role.
cocus#Detail: Person is the parent of Thing which is modified by Person. Person is the inverse of add.
cocus#Corresponding_Author: The Corresponding Author is the parent of the user and the parent of the Thing. The user is the parent of the Thing and the Corresponding Author is the child of the Corresponding Author.
cocus#Reviewer_Role: The Reviewer Role is the parent of the Committe Role and the Author Role. The Committe Role is the parent of the Author Role.
cocus#Event_Approval: Event Approval is the parent of Activity which is the child of Event Creation.
cocus#Registration: The Help Request is sent by the user who has registered and has resulted in a Help Request. The Help Request is a child of Committee and Misc. Committee is the parent of the Help Request.
cocus#Full_Paper: The full paper is the parent of both the document and the abstract. Paper is the parent of both the document and the submission.
cocus#Research_Topic: The Review Form is the parent of the Preview and the Review Form. It is also the parent of the Event Setup which is the parent of the Submission Template.
cocus#Conference: Paper Typologies is the parent of Conference and Event Setup which is the parent of Thing. Paper Typologies is the parent of Event Setup which is the parent of Conference.
cocus#Assistance: The parent of the Help Request is the parent of the Activity which is part of the Registration activity. The Activity is also part of the Help Request.
cocus#Email_Template: The email template is the parent of Event Setup which is the event that is the parent of Symposium and Thing. Event Tracks is the parent of Event Setup which is the event that is the parent of Event.
